 Samtel inks deal with HAL

 OUR CORRESPONDENT

 HAL chairman Ashok K. Baweja (left) with Samtel CMD Satish Kaura (right) in New Delhi on Monday. Picture by Ramakant Kushwaha

 New Delhi, July 10: Samtel, the electronics display systems maker, and state-owned aviation firm Hindustan Aeronautics Ltd (HAL) today signed a joint venture agreement to develop and manufacture avionics display systems.

 Samtel will hold a 60 per cent stake in the venture, Samtel-HAL Display Systems, and HAL 40 per cent. This is the first public-private partnership in defence avionics.

 Officials said the joint venture is targeting a revenue of Rs 300 crore over the next 4-5 years.

 Initially, the company will manufacture multi-functional and head-up displays required for HALs star programmes like intermediate jet trainer, light combat aircraft and SU-30 MKI. Later, it will make civil and industrial products for the domestic and international markets.

 HAL chairman Ashok K. Baweja said the joint venture would synergise the capabilities of the two companies to become a globally competitive business entity.

 Samtel CMD Satish Kaura said the company would invest in the joint venture in two phases. 




